04587nam a22006255i 9780520914728DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209147287 a10.1525/97805209147282doi  a(DE-B1597)648680  a(OCoLC)1414457474  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPN1995b.I1813 1998eb 7aPER0040002bisacsh04a791.43/01/52211 aIampolski/Ram, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMemory of Tiresias :bIntertextuality and Film /cIampolski/Ram; ed. by Mikhail Iampolski, Harsha Ram. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (285 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tACKNOWLEDGEMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I. BASIC CONCEPTS -- tChapter 1. Cinema and the Theory of Intertextuality -- tPART II. NARRATIVE'S WAY: D. W. GRIFFITH -- tChapter 2. Repressing the Source: D. W. Griffith and Browning -- tChapter 3. Intertextuality and the Evolution of Cinematic Language: Griffith and the Poetic Tradition -- tPART III. BEYOND NARRATIVE: AVANT-GARDE CINEMA -- tChapter 4. Cinematic Language as Quotation: Cendrars and Léger -- tChapter 5. Intertext against Intertext: Bunuel and Dali's Un Chien andalou -- tPART IV. THEORISTS WHO PRACTICED -- tChapter 6. The Hero as an "Intertextual Body -- tChapter 7. The Invisible Text as a Universal Equivalent -- tCONCLUSION -- tNOTES -- tWORKS CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concept of intertextuality has proven of inestimable value in recent attempts to understand the nature of literature and its relation to other systems of cultural meaning. In The Memory of Tiresias, Mikhail Iamposlki presents the first sustained attempt to develop a theory of cinematic intertextuality.Building on the insights of semiotics and contemporary film theory, Iampolski defines cinema as a chain of transparent, mimetic fragments intermixed with "ations he calls "textual anomalies." These challenge the normalization of meaning and seek to open reading out onto the unlimited field of cultural history, which is understood in texts as a semiotically active extract, already inscribed.Quotations obstruct mimesis and are consequently transformed in the process of semiosis, an operation that Iampolski defines as reading in an aura of enigma. In a series of brilliant analyses of films by D.W. Griffith, Sergei Eisenstein, and Luis Buñuel, he presents different strategies of intertextual reading in their work. His book suggests the continuing centrality of semiotic analysis and is certain to interest film historians and theorists, as well as readers in cultural and literary studies.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIntertextuality. 0aMotion pictures. 4aFilm. 4aGeneral. 4aPerforming Arts. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aEisenstein, Sergei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIampolski, Mikhail, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLieutenant Kizhe, Iurii Tynianov\x27s, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRam, Harsha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008530540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091472840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520914728423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520914728/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles